ssibility of whole streets, routes, parks, and squares, and even entire cities and regions. Today, access is a key concept in the most disparate areas of life. Thus, it is also a matter of access to knowledge and education, access to knowledge media like the Internet, access to healthcare, access to languages, etc. In thirteen articles, this book deals with this world of access in architecture, city planning, and neighboring fields. Topics include ensuring the accessibility of entire urban areas, renewing that of areas that were previously utilized differently, including the general populace in concept planning, and how architecture can help provide access to a better quality of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchitecturexHuman factors. 0aBarrier-free design. 0aCity planning. 0aUniversal design. 4aaccess. 4aarchitecture. 4amobility. 4aurbanism. 7aARCHITECTURE / General.2bisacsh1 aBöhme, Gernot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrist, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChrist, Wolfgang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCroll, Jutta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdinger, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, Jonas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoose, Willi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReinhard, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSieverts, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimmen, Jeannot, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSoehlke, Cor